    hidden: [
      { word: 'BRINE',  story: "The ocean is about 3.5 percent salt — but that ratio varies. The Dead Sea is nearly ten times saltier, dense enough that human bodies float without effort. The word salary comes from the Latin sal, because Roman soldiers were sometimes paid in salt or given an allowance to buy it. Salt has been currency, preservative, and medicine for most of human history. At the cellular level, it is still what we are made of." },
      { word: 'ATOLL',  story: "Charles Darwin proposed his theory of coral atoll formation in 1842 — nearly two decades before On the Origin of Species, and long before any technology existed to verify it. He argued that atolls were reefs growing upward around slowly sinking volcanic islands, leaving only the ring when the island finally disappeared. In 1952, a drill on Eniwetok Atoll struck volcanic basalt 1,400 meters below the coral. Darwin was right." },
      { word: 'HAVEN',  story: "\"The cure for anything is salt water: sweat, tears, or the sea.\" — Isak Dinesen, Seven Gothic Tales, 1934. Dinesen was the pen name of Karen Blixen, a Danish writer who ran a coffee farm in Kenya for seventeen years. She wrote the line in the middle of financial ruin, a failed marriage, and the beginning of exile. It has since appeared on refrigerator magnets, tattoos, and sympathy cards worldwide — almost always without attribution." },
      { word: 'SPUME',  story: "The foam at the edge of a breaking wave is called spume. It forms when dissolved organic matter — algae, fish scales, the proteins of a billion tiny organisms — gets churned into bubbles by the wave's collapse. It is the sea's own lather, its evidence of life made briefly visible. On a calm day it collects in drifts at the tide line. It lasts about ten seconds before the water pulls it back." },
      { word: 'NEAP',   story: "Twice a month, when the sun, moon, and Earth form a right angle rather than a straight line, the tides grow smaller — neither fully pulling nor fully pushing. These are neap tides. The name comes from an Old English word meaning scanty, lacking. Spring tides — the large ones at new and full moon — arrive in all four seasons. The word comes not from the season but from the Old English springan: to leap." },
      { word: 'GYRE',   story: "The North Pacific Subtropical Gyre is a slow clockwise current the size of a continent, driven by wind and the rotation of the Earth. At its center, where currents converge and debris accumulates, lies the Great Pacific Garbage Patch — roughly 79,000 metric tons of plastic spread across an area twice the size of Texas. It is not a solid island. It is a diffuse soup, mostly invisible from the surface. The gyre has been collecting it since the 1950s." },
      { word: 'SWASH',  story: "The sheet of water that surges up the beach after a wave breaks is called swash. The water that flows back down is backwash. The line where swash stops and reverses — where the sand is darkest, where the shells concentrate, where children dare each other to stand — is the swash limit. Coastal engineers study it carefully. Most beachgoers discover it instinctively, usually by misjudging it once." },
      { word: 'ERODE',  story: "The Yorkshire coast has been retreating for two thousand years. The Romans built a garrison town on the headland; it is under the North Sea now. The cliffs there erode at roughly half a meter per year — slow enough that no one notices season to season, fast enough that thirty villages have disappeared since the Normans arrived. Their names still appear in medieval tax records. The land beneath them is gone." },
      { word: 'FLEET',  story: "In August 1588, the Spanish Armada — 130 ships, 18,000 soldiers, the most powerful naval force in the world — sailed for England and was destroyed not by the English navy but by weather. English ships harassed them up the Channel; Atlantic gales finished the job. Fewer than 70 of the 130 ships returned to Spain. Queen Elizabeth I had medals struck with a Latin inscription: Flavit Jehovah et Dissipati Sunt. God blew, and they were scattered." },
      { word: 'SIREN',  story: "In Greek mythology, the Sirens were not mermaids — they were women with the bodies of birds. The mermaid version appeared gradually through the Middle Ages, merging with separate fish-woman traditions from Babylonian and Celtic mythology. By the Renaissance the bird form was almost entirely forgotten. Homer never described what they looked like at all. He only described the singing, and what it did to men who heard it." }
    ]
