    hidden: [
      { word: 'VAST',    story: "\"Space is big. You just won't believe how vastly, hugely, mind-bogglingly big it is.\" — Douglas Adams, The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy" },
      { word: 'DRIFT',   story: "Objects left in low Earth orbit don't stay there forever — atmospheric drag slowly pulls them down. But objects left in higher orbits will remain for millions of years. The Voyager 1 probe, launched in 1977, is now over 23 billion kilometers away and still sending data. It will drift through interstellar space long after every human alive today is gone." },
      { word: 'ABYSS',   story: "The Boötes Void is a region of space roughly 330 million light-years across containing almost nothing — no galaxies, no stars, no known matter. It is so empty that astronomers initially assumed their instruments were broken. Its existence is not fully explained by any current model of the universe." },
      { word: 'COSMIC',  story: "\"The cosmos is within us. We are made of star-stuff. We are a way for the universe to know itself.\" — Carl Sagan, Cosmos" },
      { word: 'LAUNCH',  story: "\"Earth is the cradle of humanity, but one cannot remain in the cradle forever.\" — Konstantin Tsiolkovsky, pioneer of astronautics, written in 1895 — 58 years before the first satellite launch" },
      { word: 'BURST',   story: "In 1054 AD, astronomers in China, Japan, and the Arab world all independently recorded a new star so bright it was visible in daylight for 23 days. No European record exists — historians believe the Church considered it theologically inconvenient. What they saw was a supernova burst. Its remnant, the Crab Nebula, is still expanding today at 1,500 kilometers per second." },
      { word: 'RISE',    story: "When Apollo 8 astronaut William Anders looked back at Earth from lunar orbit on Christmas Eve 1968, he grabbed a camera and took a photograph without authorization — it wasn't in the flight plan. That image, Earthrise, became one of the most reproduced photographs in history and is credited with launching the modern environmental movement." },
      { word: 'SCALE',   story: "Light leaving the edge of the observable universe takes 46 billion light-years to reach us — even though the universe is only 13.8 billion years old. The difference is because space itself has been expanding the whole time. The universe is not just big. It is actively getting bigger, in every direction, right now." },
      { word: 'COSMOS',  story: "When Carl Sagan's original Cosmos series aired in 1980, it was the most watched PBS program in history. Sagan received thousands of letters from viewers who said it changed how they thought about their lives. One letter, from a prisoner, said: \"I look up at the stars now and I don't feel so trapped.\" Sagan wrote back to him personally." },
      { word: 'PULSAR',  story: "Pulsars are so metronomically precise that they were briefly considered as the basis for a universal timekeeping standard — more accurate than atomic clocks. The most stable known pulsar loses less than a millisecond every 300 million years. They are the most accurate clocks in the universe, built by physics, running since before Earth existed." },
      { word: 'LIGHT',   story: "The speed of light was first measured by Ole Rømer in 1676 by observing inconsistencies in the timing of Jupiter's moons. He calculated roughly 220,000 km/s — about 27% too slow, but the correct order of magnitude. The precise value, 299,792,458 meters per second, took three more centuries to nail down. Since 1983, the meter has been defined in terms of light speed rather than the other way around. We no longer measure how fast light travels. We use light to define what a meter is." },
      { word: 'LUNAR',   story: "The Moon is moving away from Earth at roughly 3.8 centimeters per year — the same rate your fingernails grow. It has been receding since it formed 4.5 billion years ago. Eventually it will be too far away for total solar eclipses: the Moon's disk will no longer exactly cover the Sun's. Every total solar eclipse that will ever be possible is happening now, in this geological era, by coincidence of distance. Future generations will only see rings." },
      { word: 'DWARF',   story: "Pluto was discovered in 1930 by Clyde Tombaugh, a 24-year-old amateur astronomer working at Lowell Observatory for $125 a month. For 76 years it was the ninth planet. In 2006, the International Astronomical Union redefined \"planet\" in a way Pluto did not meet, and reclassified it as a dwarf planet. Tombaugh had died in 1997, nine years before the vote. His ashes are aboard the New Horizons spacecraft, which flew past Pluto in 2015." },
      { word: 'EPOCH',   story: "The universe is approximately 13.8 billion years old. The first stars formed at roughly year 200 million. Earth formed at year 9.2 billion. Life began at year 9.7 billion. The dinosaurs appeared at year 13.65 billion and went extinct at year 13.795 billion. Humans have existed for approximately the last 300,000 years — the last 0.002% of cosmic time. Everything you have ever known or will know fits in that margin." },
      { word: 'SHIFT',   story: "In 1929, Edwin Hubble published data showing that almost every galaxy is moving away from us, and that farther galaxies are receding faster. The light from these galaxies is red-shifted — stretched toward the red end of the spectrum by the expansion of space. This was the observational proof that the universe is expanding. Hubble didn't interpret it that way immediately. The calculation was done by Georges Lemaître two years earlier, but Lemaître published in French, in a Belgian journal, and Hubble got credit for the discovery he was slower to reach." },
      { word: 'GIANT',   story: "When our Sun exhausts its hydrogen fuel in roughly five billion years, it will expand into a red giant, growing large enough to swallow Mercury, Venus, and possibly Earth. The process takes about a billion years. During that phase, the habitable zone will shift outward — Europa and other moons of Jupiter may briefly become candidates for liquid water. What survives after the Sun collapses into a white dwarf will be a different solar system than the one we know." },
      { word: 'SIGNAL',  story: "On August 15, 1977, an astronomer at Ohio State University's radio telescope detected a signal so unusual he circled it on the printout and wrote \"Wow!\" in the margin. The signal lasted 72 seconds — exactly as long as the telescope's observation window allowed — and has never been detected again. It came from the direction of the constellation Sagittarius. No explanation has been confirmed. It remains the strongest candidate for an extraterrestrial signal ever received." },
      { word: 'SILENT',  story: "Sound cannot travel through space. The explosions of supernovae, the collisions of galaxies, the jets of black holes — all of it occurs in absolute silence from any external perspective. When films play sounds in space, they are choosing narrative comfort over accuracy. The universe has no acoustics. Everything that happens in it — every detonation, every collision, every birth and death of a star — happens in a silence too total to imagine." },
      { word: 'FROZEN',  story: "Europa, one of Jupiter's moons, has a global ocean of liquid water beneath 10 to 30 kilometers of ice — containing roughly twice the water in all of Earth's oceans combined. The water is kept liquid by tidal flexing from Jupiter's gravity. Astronomers consider it one of the most promising places in the solar system to find life. We have never touched its surface. The ice above is pristine and unbroken, and beneath it something we have never seen." },
      { word: 'PLANET',  story: "The word comes from the Greek planetes — wanderer — because planets appear to move against the fixed background of stars. For most of human history there were seven: the Sun, Moon, Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter, and Saturn. The outer planets weren't discovered until telescopes existed. The count has changed continuously since then: eight, nine, eight again. Every time we refine the definition, we change the number of things that meet it." }
    ]
